The Dark Knight is a 2008 superhero film directed by Christopher Nolan, based on the DC Comics character Batman. The film stars Christian Bale as Batman/Bruce Wayne, Michael Caine as Alfred Pennyworth, Heath Ledger as The Joker, Aaron Eckhart as Harvey Dent/Two-Face, Maggie Gyllenhaal as Rachel Dawes, Gary Oldman as Commissioner Gordon, and Morgan Freeman as Lucius Fox.

The film was well received by critics and audiences, and is considered one of the best superhero films of all time. It was nominated for 8 Academy Awards, winning two: Best Supporting Actor for Ledger and Best Sound Editing.

The film opens with a bank heist being carried out by the Joker, who shoots a security guard before making his way to the vault. He opens the safe and takes the money before leaving the bank. At the same time, Batman arrives at the scene and witnesses the security guard's death. He then follows the Joker to his hideout and confronts him.

The Joker reveals that he has a bomb strapped to his chest that will detonate if anyone tries to stop him from escaping. He threatens to detonate it unless Batman agrees to his demands: that he kills Harvey Dent, who is Gotham City's district attorney, and that Batman gives himself up as well. Batman refuses to comply with either of these demands, and the Joker detonates his bomb, killing himself in the process.

Batman then returns to Gotham City with Harvey Dent's body in tow, where he is hailed as a hero by the citizens. However, Dent's true nature is revealed when it is discovered that he was actually a corrupt politician who had been using his position to cover up organized crime activities in Gotham City. As a result of this revelation, Batman becomes a target for Dent's former allies in organized crime.

He begins training under the guidance of Lucius Fox, who teaches him how to use his wealth and resources to become a better vigilante.

The Joker returns in a new form: as a disfigured clown who taunts Batman with riddles and challenges him to kill him again. This time around, however, Batman refuses to give into the Joker's demands and continues to try and stop him from harming others. As a result of this confrontation, the Joker is ultimately killed by Commissioner Gordon using a shotgun blast from behind cover.

Batman then confronts Harvey Dent's former allies in organized crime and destroys their operations once and for all. He also decides to give himself up to the police in order to take responsibility for Dent's crimes and protect Gotham City from any future threats.

The film ends with Bruce Wayne becoming more determined than ever before to protect Gotham City from crime and corruption. He returns home after defeating the Joker for good and assumes the role of Mayor of Gotham City once again.
